## What I Worked On Today

Three AWS-native services are the technical backbone of the OpenMRS continuous monitoring program: AWS Config (configuration compliance monitoring), AWS Security Hub (findings aggregation and security posture assessment), and AWS Audit Manager (evidence collection for compliance frameworks). Today I work through each service in detail — what it does, how it connects to the OpenMRS security controls, what specific rules and checks are relevant, and what the tooling cannot do that still requires human judgment.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified all three tools today is understanding the distinction between automated detection and automated assurance.

Automated detection means the tool identifies when something is wrong — a Config rule flags a non-compliant resource, Security Hub aggregates a finding, Audit Manager collects evidence of a configuration state. This is genuinely valuable and dramatically more reliable than manual periodic checks for catching configuration drift quickly.

Automated assurance — the conclusion that because the tools are running, the system is secure — is a dangerous overclaim. The tools detect what they are configured to detect. They cannot detect what they are not looking for. Config rules catch known compliance violations against defined standards; they do not catch novel misconfigurations that no rule was written to address. Security Hub aggregates findings from services that are enabled and properly configured; it does not generate findings for services it is not integrated with. Audit Manager collects evidence that controls are configured; it does not verify that configured controls are producing their intended security outcomes.

The M-002 finding from Day 71 illustrates this precisely: AWS Config detected the IAM password policy drift immediately and flagged it correctly. But Config did not detect — and could not detect — the process failure that caused the drift: the IT Administrator making a security-relevant change without CM-3 compliance. The technical misconfiguration was caught automatically. The process failure required human review of the CloudTrail log to identify the root cause.

Automated detection is a powerful tool. Substituting it for genuine security judgment is how organizations end up with well-monitored systems that are nonetheless insecure in ways the monitoring never catches.

