## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The alert fatigue problem — where security teams become overwhelmed by the volume of automated findings and begin unconsciously filtering out legitimate alerts alongside noise — was directly illustrated by the **2020 SolarWinds breach**. Post-incident analysis found that security monitoring tools at many affected organizations had generated alerts during the intrusion period, but the alert volume was high enough that the SolarWinds-specific indicators were not identified as distinctive from the background alert noise.

For OpenMRS, the tuning discipline — suppressing expected findings with documented rationale, setting severity thresholds that match the ISSO's actual response capacity, reviewing the suppression list quarterly — is not about reducing work for its own sake. It is about ensuring that when a genuine HIGH or CRITICAL finding appears, it stands out against a managed background rather than competing with 50 other MEDIUM findings that have been present for months.

Security Hub's value is a function of the discipline applied to its configuration. An untuned Security Hub with 200 open findings of varying relevance is less useful than a tuned Security Hub with 15 findings that all represent genuine, actionable issues. The difference is not the tool — it is the ISSO's investment in maintaining the signal-to-noise ratio.

