## What I Am Still Thinking About

AWS Audit Manager supports NIST SP 800-53 and HIPAA as built-in frameworks, which maps well to the OpenMRS authorization requirements. But Audit Manager's framework mapping is imperfect — the automated evidence collection covers the controls where AWS infrastructure configuration is the primary implementation mechanism, but many NIST SP 800-53 controls have significant non-technical components that Audit Manager cannot assess.

IR-3 (Incident Response Testing) is a clear example: Audit Manager cannot collect evidence of a tabletop exercise or technical simulation. The ISSO must manually upload that evidence to the Audit Manager assessment. AT-2 (Security Awareness Training) is similar — Audit Manager cannot collect evidence of training completion rates or curriculum content.

For the re-authorization assessment, the evidence package will consist of Audit Manager automated evidence for the infrastructure-layer controls plus ISSO-compiled manual evidence for the procedure and training controls. Understanding which controls fall into which category — before the re-authorization assessment begins — prevents the gap where the ISSO assumes Audit Manager has covered a control that is actually not in scope for automated collection.

I want to create a control-to-evidence-source mapping before the first annual continuous monitoring summary is due — for each of the 80+ controls in the OpenMRS SSP, documenting whether the primary evidence source is automated (Audit Manager / Config / Security Hub) or manual (ISSO test records, training completion reports, restoration test documentation). That mapping turns the annual evidence compilation from a reactive scramble into a checklist-driven process.

